[
    "Executive Summary",
    "A statistical test was performed to determine whether employee salaries differ across the organization’s departments.",
    "Using a Kruskal‑Wallis H test, the analysis produced an H‑statistic of 12.4 with a p‑value of 0.002.",
    "Because the p‑value is well below the conventional 0.05 threshold, we conclude that there is a statistically significant difference in median salary among departments.",
    "The confidence in this finding is High, reflecting the strong signal from the executed step and the absence of any errors or data quality concerns.",
    "Data Overview",
    "Rows: 150 employee records",
    "Columns: 4 variables",
    "department – categorical identifier of the employee’s functional area",
    "salary – numeric compensation amount (the primary metric of interest)",
    "years_experience – numeric tenure in the workforce",
    "location – categorical geographic identifier",
    "The dataset provides a balanced view of the workforce, allowing a non‑parametric comparison of salary distributions across departments without assuming normality.",
    "Analysis Results",
    "The only analytical step executed was an exploratory data analysis (EDA) focused on salary distribution across departments.",
    "The chosen method, a Kruskal‑Wallis H test followed by Dunn post‑hoc comparisons (though post‑hoc results are not provided), is appropriate for comparing more than two independent groups when the salary variable may not meet parametric assumptions.",
    "Finding: The overall test indicates that at least one department’s salary distribution differs from the others.",
    "Confidence Level: High – derived from the “high” confidence signal attached to Step 1 and the successful completion of the test without errors.",
    "Statistical Findings",
    "H‑statistic | 12.4 | Measures the degree of divergence among department salary ranks; larger values suggest greater differences.",
    "p‑value | 0.002 | Probability of observing such an H‑statistic under the null hypothesis of equal salary distributions.",
    "Since 0.002 < 0.05, the null hypothesis is rejected.",
    "The low p‑value provides strong evidence that salary is not uniformly distributed across departments.",
    "Limitations & Confidence",
    "Scope of Analysis: Only a single non‑parametric test was performed; no additional modeling (e.g., regression controlling for experience or location) was conducted.",
    "Post‑hoc Details: While Dunn post‑hoc was mentioned in the methodology, specific pairwise comparison results are not available, limiting insight into which departments differ.",
    "Data Granularity: The report does not include descriptive statistics (means, medians, interquartile ranges) for each department, which would help quantify the magnitude of differences.",
    "Confidence Assessment: All steps completed successfully, and the confidence signal for the executed step is “high.”",
    "Consequently, the overall confidence in the primary finding is High.",
    "No failures or retries were recorded, so there are no additional limitations from execution errors.",
    "Recommendations",
    "Conduct Pairwise Comparisons: Run the Dunn post‑hoc test and report adjusted p‑values to identify specific department pairs with significant salary gaps.",
    "Incorporate Covariates: Extend the analysis with a multivariate model (e.g., linear regression or mixed‑effects model) that includes years_experience and location to determine whether observed salary differences persist after accounting for these factors.",
    "Visualize Distributions: Produce boxplots or violin plots of salary by department to communicate the practical size of differences to stakeholders.",
    "Review Compensation Policy: If certain departments consistently show lower median salaries, consider a compensation benchmarking exercise to ensure internal equity and market competitiveness.",
    "Monitor Over Time: Establish a periodic (e.g., quarterly) salary audit using the same methodology to track changes and assess the impact of any policy adjustments.",
    "By following these steps, the organization can move from a statistical indication of disparity to actionable insights that support fair and strategic compensation management."
